i## What's Going On		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iWhen your server peers with others via BGP protocol, each route		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
icontains path information, including the origin as well as the list of		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
inodes it went through. For example, the route `172.22.76.184/29` may		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ihave the path information of `4242422547 -> 4242422601 -> 424242****` ,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iwhere `4242422547` is the origin (me by the way), and `4242422601` is		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iyour neighbor (Burble here, as an example).		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iBut since your internal networking uses OSPF, which has no idea what		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iBGP paths are, it doesn't preserve them while passing routes around.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iNow another node of yours obtained `172.22.76.184/29` via OSPF, yet		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iwithout any path information. It will then proceed to announce the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iroute with your own ASN to your peers, causing a hijack.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iHere is a graph of what's going on:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  [2547] -> [2601] -> [Your Node A] -> [Your Node B] -> [Peer of Node B]		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   2547      2547      2547             Gone!            Your ASN (BOOM)		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i             2601      2601		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i                       Your ASN		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i# Babel is Fun, Too		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThose in the Telegram group are really nice guys. As they help you in		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ifixing the problem, they also recommended Babel to you:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- Babel automatically selects the shortest path by latency.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- Babel is extremely simple to configure.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iBut they don't recommend Bird's built-in Babel support since it		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
idoesn't support selecting paths by latency.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iYou are persuaded, removed the OSPF configuration, and installed		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iBabeld. Soon each of your nodes is getting Babel routes. You waited		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ifor a few minutes. No sign of catastrophe yet.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iBut you do notice that Bird isn't announcing the routes via BGP. The		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iTelegram guys instigated you to enable the `learn` option of Bird's		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ikernel protocol:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  protocol kernel sys_kernel_v4 {		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    scan time 20;		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    # You're gonna add this line!		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    learn;		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    # Unimportant stuff redacted		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  };		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iYou do this. A few minutes later, you are called out again by people		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iin IRC and Telegram. Yes, you hijacked other's networks. Again.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i## What's Going On		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iIt is actually the same problem as the OSPF one since Babel also		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
idropped all BGP path information while passing routes around. However,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iBird ignores routing information installed to the system by other		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
irouting software by default, until you enabled `learn` .		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i## Correct Way to Do This		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- Always remember: Interior Gateway Protocols, including OSPF, Babel,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  etc, should never process BGP routing information. BGP routing		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  should be handled solely by BGP.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  - There are multiple schemes to configure BGP in a network. You may		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    refer to:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
1    Bird BGP Confederation: Configuration and Emulation	/en/article/modify-website/bird-confederation.lantian	{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    .		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- Similarly, interior routes should not be passed to BGP, unless you		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  own each and every IP that you're using internally on DN42.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- So you should set BGP's `export filter` to this in Bird:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  export filter {		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    # Only allow announcing STATIC (manually configured) and BGP routes		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    if source ~ [RTS_STATIC, RTS_BGP] then accept;		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    # Reject routes from other protocols		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    reject;		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  }		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i## Defensive Measures		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- The best countermeasure is ROA, or Route Origin Authorization. It		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  restricts the source ASN of each route.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  - For DN42, ROA configuration is generated automatically based on		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    registry data. They can be downloaded from		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
h    DN42 Wiki's Bird Config Page	URL:https://wiki.dn42.us/howto/Bird#route-origin-authorization	{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    , and can be automatically updated with a cron job.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- If you don't want to configure ROA, you may try to peer with more		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  people.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  - Since BGP chooses the path with the least number of ASes, if		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    you're directly connected to a lot of people, your network will		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    prefer these direct routes even if someone is hijacking.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  - But this **doesn't guarantee** full defense against the problem,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    for example:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    - The path from the hijacker to you is shorter than the real AS.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    - The path from the hijacker and from real AS is of equal length,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      and your routing software chooses one randomly.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    - You have DN42 Community Filter, and for some reason, prefers the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      hijacker's route over the real ones.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i# Route Flapping		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iRoute flapping is a whole range of errors that cause one problem: they		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
icause the BGP routing software to frequently switch (or flap) the best		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iroute they chose. Since the best route gets announced to other nodes		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ivia peering, the flapping sets off a chained reaction, where multiple		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iconnected nodes will flap together for one node's mistake. Eventually,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ithe problem will be distributed to the whole network.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThis process consumes a significant amount of bandwidth or traffic.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iSince many people in DN42 use cheap VPSes for nodes, there are only		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
itwo possible outcomes eventually:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i1. Your peer found out about the abnormal traffic and cut the peering		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   to you.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i2. Your hosting provider (or even your peer's provider) found out of		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   your high bandwidth consumption (or using up your traffic limit)		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   and shut down the VPS.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iIn addition, route flapping may cause severe impacts:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- If the problematic AS peered with many other ASes, even if you		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  disconnected from it, the route flap may still be passed from		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  another AS to your AS again.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  - To fix the problem of one problematic AS, you may have to cut off		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    multiple ASes.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iFor example, one user in the Telegram group had a misconfiguration		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iwhile transitioning from Full-mesh + Direct connections to Multihop.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
II Always Love Niantic Network	/usr/uploads/202008/i-love-niantic-network.png	{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iHe didn't disconnect BGP in the process, and the Babel configuration		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ierror caused large amounts of routes to be announced and withdrawn.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iBecause of the chain reaction and the number of peerings the guy has		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iset up, multiple large ASes had to disconnect from each other to		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
icontrol the problem (before he woke up).		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
